      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes vendor-supplied benchmark suite for incompressible rotating-frame problems; at least one published benchmark result reproduced within 2% for pressure and velocity.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2021R2 has been verified against the lid-driven cavity and rotating-disk benchmark cases supplied by the vendor. Reproduced benchmark pressure coefficient within 1.4% and velocity profiles within 1.8% of published reference solutions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for hemolysis index QoI less than 5% on the medium-to-fine refinement level; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed (coarse: 4.2M cells, medium: 9.8M cells, fine: 22.1M cells). GCI for the normalized hemolysis index between medium and fine meshes was 3.1%, satisfying the 5% threshold. The medium mesh was selected for production runs balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental validation conditions match at least 3 of 5 target operating points; fluid properties (viscosity, density) replicated within 5% of clinical blood analog.",
      "rationale": "Bench experiments were conducted using a glycerol-water blood analog (viscosity 3.5 cP, density 1050 kg/m³) matching clinical whole blood properties within 2%. Three of five target flow-speed operating points were reproduced in the validation test rig; the remaining two fall within the interpolated range of tested conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) within 15% of experimentally measured values across all validated operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values were compared against bench measurements at three validated operating points. Deviations were 8.2%, 11.4%, and 6.7% respectively, all within the 15% acceptance criterion. Agreement is considered adequate for relative ranking of operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (NIH, RH, peak shear stress) are directly linked to the clinical hemolysis acceptance criterion RH < 1 and are established in peer-reviewed hemolysis modeling literature.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis and relative hemolysis index are the standard QoIs used in FDA-recognized hemolysis modeling guidance and the peer-reviewed literature. Peak scalar shear stress is included as a secondary QoI to capture sub-lethal damage accumulation pathways relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry is the FDA generic centrifugal pump or a device with comparable flow regime (Re, flow coefficient) within 20%; operating range overlaps with COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same geometry used in production simulations. The operating range tested (2.5–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) spans the COU envelope, providing direct relevance to the clinical use scenario."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error beyond discretization is not required to be separately characterized at Model Risk Level 2 for this COU. Vendor verification activities and the discretization error assessment together provide adequate confidence in numerical accuracy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Formal use-error analysis is not required at Model Risk Level 2. Simulation setup was reviewed by a second analyst and boundary conditions were independently confirmed against the test protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model selection justified by literature precedent and sensitivity analysis; SST k-omega turbulence model used with Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance in rotating-passage flows and its use in prior FDA pump validation studies. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law is the most widely cited model for this device class. No failure modes have been observed in prior applications of this model combination to centrifugal blood pump geometries, and no contraindications have been reported in the literature reviewed during model selection. The model form is therefore considered appropriate for the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All boundary conditions traceable to measured or published values; inlet velocity profile, rotational speed, and fluid properties documented with uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Inlet velocity profiles were derived from ultrasonic flow meter measurements (uncertainty ±2%). Rotational speed was set from tachometer readings (±10 RPM). Fluid properties were measured using a cone-and-plate viscometer. All inputs are documented in the simulation input file archive with traceability to raw measurement records."
    },
